observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor require the Inventory Committee to perform the following procedures to facilitate the recording of the 75 per cent of the local roads, as well as the remaining 25 per cent from the Registry of Public Infrastructures, to the books of accounts of the City:
a) Prioritize the conduct of inventory of the local roads under the City's jurisdiction acquired in CY 2015 backwards;
b) Reconcile the results of the inventory and road map with the local road accounts recorded in the Registry of Public Infrastructures, and thereafter, prepare the Schedule of Local Roads and Road Networks/Working Paper on the distribution of costs for the road components;
c) Based on such schedule/working paper, depreciate the carrying amount of the existing roads and their components to reflect the asset in its used condition. The depreciated cost/fair value of the local roads shall then be recorded in the general ledger; and
d) Prepare and submit to the Office of the Auditor the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Networks not later than January 31 of each year.
We also recommended that the City Accounting Office and General Services Office prepare and maintain separate Subsidiary Ledgers/Local Road Network Ledger Cards (LRNLCs) and Local Road Network Property Cards (LRNPCs), respectively, for each local road to ensure proper recording and control of the assets.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
a) City Treasurer to cancel the stale checks which are in his custody and return the original Disbursement Voucher (DV) and supporting documents to the Accountant who shall prepare a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record the transaction as Accounts Payable. For stale checks, send written notices to the payees so that appropriate remedial actions can be undertaken to replace the said stale checks;
b) City Treasurer to make regular monitoring and review of the status of checks issued which remained outstanding for a relatively long period of time and to send written notices to the payee for the existence of the checks due to them at least one month before they become stale;
c) City Treasurer to secure the corresponding bank credit memorandum or any other appropriate document for the P120,000.00 reconciling item to validate the same;
d) City Treasurer and the City Accountant to coordinate with each other to locate the documents necessary to support the adjustments to be made in the books of accounts; and
e) City Accountant to draw the necessary JEVs to take up in the accounting books the valid reconciling items.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the City Accountant and Acting General Services Officer to continue their efforts to reconcile and determine the nature of the discrepancies noted in the PPE account and make the necessary adjustments/corrections, whenever applicable.
We also recommended to consider all possible remedies to the negative observations and problems encountered in the conduct of physical inventory.  Specifically, the General Service Officer should ensure that:
Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) and/or Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) are issued for all PPE items issued to actual recipients and/or end-users and renewed every three years;
issued  PPE items are returned  to the GSO before the issuance of Agency Clearance for those officials and employees who will apply for  retirement, transfer of office and/or death;
demolished constructed buildings, roads and bridges, deep wells and other assets are inventoried and  requested to be  dropped from the books;
equipment covered  with Acknowledgement Receipt for Equipment (ARE) and/or Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) are included in the inventory report;
proper turnover of PPE items from outgoing and incoming officials particularly in the barangay level is strictly observed/ made;
Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC), Real Property Ledger Card (RPLC) and Property Cards per category of Plant, Property and Equipment are properly maintained and updated;  and
Donated properties are properly documented and covered by Deeds of Donation and Acceptance of Donations.
We further recommended that the City Mayor direct the General Services    Officer to facilitate the disposal of unserviceable properties and see to it that the proper procedure and necessary supporting documents are available for audit before any disposal of unserviceable property is undertaken.

We recommended that City Mayor direct the Acting General Services Officer to furnish the Auditor with copies of Purchase/Work Orders and delivery documents within the prescribed period in compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-002 dated May 18, 2009.   Specifically the General Services Officer should see to it that:
Purchase Orders  prepared contained accurate and complete information;
Control mechanism and close monitoring in the issuance of Purchase Order is strictly observed to avoid another issuance of the same PO Number and use of Suffix “A” in numbering of PO and discrepancies in the information stated in the PO and its supporting documents;
PO is not duly signed by the Local Chief Executivebefore issuance to the supplier/contractor and  that the “Conforme” portion is   acknowledged and dated by the supplier/contractor on or after the date of the PO; and
PO Numbers are issued sequentially and refrain from accommodating PO Number reservations unless supported by complete and accurate documents.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the:
City Budget Officer to ensure that  proper utilization of the  Special  Education Fund (SEF) is strictly observed;
Former, Schools Division Superintendent to submit the breakdown of the P13,800.00 cost per participant including  justifications on why the said transaction was charged to SEF and why the activity was held in Puerto Princesa City ;
City Accountant to submit the necessary required documents to the Office of the Auditor for review and evaluation to avoid possible audit suspension/disallowance; and
City Budget Officer to restore the amount of P1,720,147.39 from the General Fund to the Special Education Fund,  otherwise the same will be disallowed in audit.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the concerned City officials and employees to adopt and implement control and monitoring system in the use of mobile phones.  Specifically, the following actions should be undertaken:
Choose and maintain only one cellular/mobile phone provider/network;
Pre-termination and Upgrading of Mobile unit and post-paid plans should be charged to the personal account of the requesting subscriber and refund the amount of P79,200.00 relative to said transactions          (Annex 19.2) ;
Submit copies of Statement of Accounts (SOA) for postpaid plans and complete quantity of prepaid cards.  Otherwise, refund the amount of  P47,597.34 and P204,797.03 for undocumented mobile claims    (Annexes 19.3 and 19.4);
Stop the practice of submitting expired prepaid card. Replace with appropriate prepaid cards. Otherwise,  refund the amount of P75,723.94 (Annex 19. 4) for the said transactions; and
Submit justification for the amount of P20,938.00 and P7,400.00, respectively for prepaid cards with no specific expiration dates and/ or invalid prepaid cards. Otherwise refund the said amount (Annex 19.4).
We also recommended that the City Mayor, City Council and the Finance Committee consider possible reduction in the amount of monthly allocation for mobile phones and choose only one from either postpaid or prepaid promo plan, practically consumable and within reasonable limits.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the City Disaster Risk Reduction Management Officer (CDRRMO) to ensure that CDRRMF are utilized to support only disaster risk management activities and the City Budget Officer to properly identify the correct charging of accounts.  Other concerned City officials and employees shall see to it that:
Purchase Orders are properly and completely filled up and date of delivery specified;
Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR) are duly signed and dated;
Warranty Period are clearly indicated;
Items issued are provided with Property Numbers;
Individual Property Acknowledgement Report (PAR) is issued to each recipient (BHW);
Proper monitoring and control are strictly observed  considering that the recipients (BHWs) of the tablets are not permanent employees of the City of Imus but were allowed to receive the tablets because they are already familiar with the barangay households and residents;
Distribution List of recipients/cluster enumerators are duly signed by GSO and CPDO;
The  10 defective tablets are  returned to suppliers for possible repair or replacement, if under warranty;
City officials and/or employees accountable for the three ( 3) tablets  lost during the training  must be identified and file a  Request from Relief of Accountability, if applicable (covered by a separate AOM);
City officials and/or employees responsible for the 103 missing/lacking chargers must account and justify the cause/whereabouts of the same. Otherwise, he/she should be held personally liable; and
Distribution and storage of the items delivered from the GSO to the CPDO (end-user/project in charge) are properly documented, coordinated and monitored.
